.TH LAZYSYSTEMD 1 "March 2025" "lazysystemd 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
lazysystemd \- Terminal UI for monitoring and controlling systemd services
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lazysystemd
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lazysystemd
is a terminal user interface (TUI) application for monitoring and controlling
systemd services, inspired by lazydocker.
.PP
The application displays a split-pane interface:
.IP \(bu 2
Left pane: List of configured services with status indicators
.IP \(bu 2
Right pane: Recent logs for the selected service
.IP \(bu 2
Footer: Keybindings and status messages
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-config\fR \fIPATH\fR
Path to configuration file (default: /etc/lazysystemd/config.yaml or ./config.yaml)
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-help\fR
Display help message
.SH CONFIGURATION
The configuration file is a YAML file listing systemd services to monitor:
.PP
.RS
.nf
services:
  - service1.service
  - service2.service
  - service3.service
.fi
.RE
.PP
The default configuration file location is \fI/etc/lazysystemd/config.yaml\fR.
An example configuration is provided at \fI/etc/lazysystemd/config.example.yaml\fR.
.SH KEYBINDINGS
.TP
\fB↑\fR, \fBk\fR
Move selection up
.TP
\fB↓\fR, \fBj\fR
Move selection down
.TP
\fBg\fR
Jump to top of service list
.TP
\fBG\fR
Jump to bottom of service list
.TP
\fBs\fR
Start selected service
.TP
\fBt\fR
Stop selected service
.TP
\fBr\fR
Restart selected service
.TP
\fBl\fR
Reload selected service
.TP
\fBf\fR
Toggle follow mode (live log streaming)
.TP
\fBR\fR
Force refresh service states
.TP
\fBq\fR, \fBCtrl+C\fR
Quit
.SH STATUS INDICATORS
.TP
\fB●\fR
Active and running
.TP
\fB○\fR
Inactive
.TP
\fB✗\fR
Failed
.TP
\fB→\fR
Activating
.TP
\fB←\fR
Deactivating
.TP
\fB?\fR
Unknown/Error
.SH FILES
.TP
\fI/etc/lazysystemd/config.yaml\fR
System-wide configuration file
.TP
\fI/etc/lazysystemd/config.example.yaml\fR
Example configuration file
.SH REQUIREMENTS
.B lazysystemd
requires:
.IP \(bu 2
Linux with systemd
.IP \(bu 2
\fBsystemctl\fR(1) and \fBjournalctl\fR(1) available in PATH
